&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by the[bold] Center for Near East Policy Research[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Executive Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]U[bold]NRWA[bold]'s Educational Activity in the [bold]Middle East[bold]1. 
[normal]UNRWA – the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for the Palestinian refugees in the Middle East – was established in the wake of the Arab-Israeli war of 1948 by the UN General Assembly resolution 302 (IV) of December 8, 
[normal]1948, in
[normal] order to carry out relie
[normal]f and works programs for the Palestinian war refugees. The agency began operations on May 1, 
[normal]1950. In
[normal] the absence of a solution to the refugee problem, the Assembly has repeatedly renewed UNRWA's mandate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. 
[normal]Over half of UNRWA's general budget is dedicate
[normal]d to education (381,055 million USD out of a total budget of 673,789 million USD in 2012, which makes 56.55%).
[normal] The agency also offers health, relief and social services. UNRWA provides free-of-charge basic education to children of Palestinian refugees in the Palestinian Authority-controlled West Bank, the Hamas-controlled Gaza Strip, the Israel-controlled East Jer
[normal]usalem, and in 
[normal]Jordan
[normal], 
[normal]Syria
[normal] and 
[normal]Lebanon
[normal]. In the school year of 2011/2012 it ran a total of 703 schools caring for 491,641 students. 245 of these 
[normal]schools were in the Gaza Strip and 99 were in the 
[normal]West Bank
[normal], with 225,098 and 51,695 students respectively.
[normal] T
[normal]wo of UNRWA's West Bank schools are actually located in the greater 
[normal]Jerusalem
[normal] area which was annexed to 
[normal]Israel
[normal] in 1967.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. 
[normal]Basic education means both elementary and intermediate (also called "preparatory") schools, that is, grades 1-9 or 10, depending on 
[normal]the specific school system in each country.
[normal] Only in 
[normal]Lebanon
[normal] does the Agency operate some nine high schools as well, since Palestinian students of these grades find it difficult to study in local public or private schools.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4. 
[normal]UNRWA maintains close cooperat
[normal]ion with government educational authorities in its various areas of operation. Students at UNRWA schools study the same curriculum and use the same books authorized by the host governments (except for 
[normal]East Jerusalem
[normal] where the PA curriculum and books have b
[normal]een adopted for use instead of the Israeli ones). Beside the schoolbooks issued by the respective national authorities with no involvement on UNRWA's part, the Agency has published several textbooks of its own which teach issues such as tolerance and human
[normal] rights in its schools, as it testifies: "One of our key programmes promotes human rights and non-violent communication skills, conflict resolution and tolerance."
[normal] 
[normal]However, these additional books do not usually touch sensitive issues related to the confli
[normal]ct such as the attitude to the "other" or the possibility of solving the conflict peacefully.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5. 
[normal]The use of books provided by the host governments in UNRWA's school is problematic because these books sometimes contain material that contradicts UNRWA's pro
[normal]fessed mission. Being a UN agency, UNRWA is committed to the ideal of peace and is bound by the UN's goal of solving the Middle Eastern conflict peacefully. In line with this commitment, UNRWA should also refrain from propagating hate indoctrination toward
[normal]s any group, including ethnic and religious ones. Moreover, as a UN body, UNRWA is obliged to treat all member states equally, 
[normal]and never promote against any of them attitudes of non-recognition, prejudice and stereotyped portrayal, not to mention demonizat
[normal]ion. However, the books studied in
[normal] UNRWA's schools often advocate an armed struggle against 
[normal]Israel
[normal] which is denied 
[normal]legitimacy as a sovereign state and severely demonized. 
[normal]This is the case as well with the Palestinian curriculum
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fundamentals of PA Educati[bold]on regarding the [bold]Jewish/Israeli "Other"[bold]6. 
[normal]Examination of 
[normal]some 150 textbooks of various subjects 
[normal]issued by the Palestinian Authority and 
[normal]taught in grades 1-10 at UNRWA's schools 
[normal]in the 
[normal]West Bank
[normal] and the Gaza Strip has revealed 
[normal]three main fundamental
[normal] lines
[normal] 
[normal]as far as the 
[normal]attitude to
[normal] the rival "other" within the conflict is concerned:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7. 
[normal]First: denial of legitimacy
[normal]According to the PA schoolbooks, there are no Jewish rights whatsoever in 
[normal]Palestine
[normal] – only "greedy ambitions"
[normal] [
[normal]Atmaa'
[normal]]
[normal].
[normal] There are no Jewish holy places there either – the Wailing Wall in Jerusalem, the Cave of the Patriarchs in Hebron and Rachel's 
[normal]Tomb in Bethlehem are all 
[normal]presented as
[normal] Muslim holy places usurped by Jews.
[normal] Jewish
[normal] 
[normal]cities – including Tel Aviv – are not shown 
[normal]on the map, except for one
[normal] or two
[normal] case
[normal]s
[normal]. Israel's 5.5 million Jews are not counted among the country's legitimate inhabitants while Israeli Arabs and Diaspora Palestinians are, which may present in a nutshell the essence of the perceived "Right of Return" 
[normal]– to be discussed later on: the 5.5 million Jewish illegitimate inhabitants of Palestine would leave and the 4.5 million Palestinians of the Diaspora will return and settle in their pl
[normal]ace:
