[normal]. 
[normal]The above-presented examples clearly show that
[normal] UNRWA's educational role among the Palestinians is problematic as far as peace education is concerned. One specific issue in this general context that deserves special attention is the so-called "Right of Return".
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The "Right of Return" Issue[bold] 
[normal]2
[normal]2
[normal]. 
[normal]The essence of the Middle East conflict is the century-long struggle between Jews and Palestinian Arabs over one piece of land stretching between the 
[normal]Mediterranean
[normal] and the River Jordan, which both parties regard as their historical homeland. The United Nat
[normal]ions Organization's attempt in 1947 to solve the conflict by way of partition was rejected by the Arab side which 
[normal]started
[normal] a war against the Jews in December that year. The war between the Jews and the Palestinian Arabs, to wh
[normal]om
[normal] five Arab armies joined in M
[normal]ay 1948, lasted sixteen months and ended in an Arab defeat. Both Jews and Palestinians lost in the war one percent of their respective populations. One of the results of that war was a mass exodus of Palestinians from areas taken over by the Jews, which la
[normal]ter became part of the nascent State of Israel. During subsequent years, a parallel number of Jews came to 
[normal]Israel
[normal] from the neighboring Arab countries
[normal], having mostly fled due to their deteriorating safety conditions there
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]3
[normal]. 
[normal]The Palestinian and Arab narr
[normal]ative of the Middle East conflict emphasizes what is termed "the Right of Return" which is interpreted as the personal right of every Palestinian, who left his or her home in Palestine in 1948 or afterwards, to return to it and to reclaim his or her proper
[normal]ty in full. This perceived right also applies to the refugee's descendants with no limit of number, time or place of birth.
[normal] Thus, the total number of such claimers has grown during the period that has passed since 1948 from few hundred thousands to severa
[normal]l millions. Although said to have been legally based on the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and on Resolution No. 194 adopted by the UN General Assembly on Dec. 11, 1948,
[normal] it is clear that such a claimed right has no legal precedence in history and, 
[normal]indeed, has not been applied in other cases of wartime refugees throughout the twentieth century, which witnessed a record number of such refugees.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]4
[normal]. 
[normal]Apart from its unique character in international terms, the "Right of Return" also raises serious polit
[normal]ical and human problems, since its full application would mean the destruction of the State of Israel as a Jewish state and thus deny the Jewish nation its right to self determination which has been legally recognized by virtue of the UN partition resoluti
[normal]on. Indeed, throughout the years that succeeded the establishment of 
[normal]Israel
[normal], the "Right of Return" issue was often mentioned in Arab forums within the wider context of the discussion of 
[normal]Israel
[normal]'s liquidation. In Israeli eyes, therefore, the continued persis
[normal]tence on the "Right of Return" by any Arab party betrays that party's desire to wipe 
[normal]Israel
[normal] off the map. Any impartial observer must admit that such fears are solidly grounded in light of the vast human mass involved.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]5
[normal]. 
[normal]If peace in the region is meant t
[normal]o be concluded between the Jewish State and its Arab neighbors – and it is so meant internationally – 
[normal]then
[normal] 
[normal]the "Right of Return" issue 
[normal]should 
[normal]not stand in the way to peace as it does today. That
[normal] 
[normal]is 
[normal]especially 
[normal]important 
[normal]in school, in particular 
[normal]– 
[normal]schools th
[normal]at are run by an international
[normal] body such as UNRWA, which is bound by UN resolutions regarding peace in the region and is expressly committed to the ideal of peace.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Teaching "The Right of Return" I: The Ideological Foundations[bold]2
[normal]6
[normal]. 
[normal]The "Right of Return" is
[normal] based ideologically on the argument that Palestine belongs to the Palestinian Arabs alone and that it became the focus of Jewish Zionist greedy ambitions (
[normal]atma'
[normal]) in the nineteenth century with a view to expelling or exterminating the indigenous population
[normal]. Those ambitions were supported by British imperialism in the twentieth century and culminated at the UN Partition Resolution of 1947. Then war broke out in which the Arab side was defeated and Zionist terrorist organizations expelled a whole nation from 
[normal]its homeland and established the State of Israel.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]7
[normal]. 
[normal]Quotations
[normal]"The Zionist colonialist greedy ambitions in 
[normal]Palestine
[normal] started in 1882…
[normal]The coming of the Jewish throngs to Palestine continued until 1948 and their goal was taking over the Palestinian land
[normal]s and then taking the original inhabitants' place after their expulsion or extermination…The Zionist greedy ambitions increased with the support of British Imperialism, as the British foreign minister Lord Balfour issued his declaration on November 2, 1917
[normal] which called for giving the Jews a national home in Palestine…
[normal]"
[normal](
[normal]National Education
[normal], Grade 7 (2011) 
[normal]p. 20)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]28
[normal]. 
[normal]"In the year 1947 the United Nations Organization adopted a resolution partitioning 
[normal]Palestine
[normal] between the Arabs and the Jews. Accordingly, the British Mandate over 
[normal]Palestine
[normal] ended and the Mandate government withdrew. Then war erupted between the Arabs and the Jews in 1948, which brought about the capture of part of 
[normal]Palestine
[normal] by the Jews and the oc
[normal]currence of the Catastrophe [
[normal]Nakbah
[normal]] which caused most of the Palestinians to emigrate."
[normal](
