[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Teaching "The Right of Return" II: Practice[bold]3
[normal]2
[normal]. 
[normal]The "Right of Return" is part and parcel of the discussion of the co
[normal]nflict. It appears in 
[normal]stories, such as the one in w
[normal]hich a grandfather is showing his grandson the ownership deeds of the land they owned in the Coastal Plain and "the keys to our house which we were forced to leave by the [Israeli 1948] occupation", and the grandson promises to keep it.
[normal] Besides, there are
[normal] language exercises using this theme such as the following one:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal]3
[normal]. 
[normal]"Activity 2: Let us feel in the empty space with the appropriate noun…
[normal]The [refugee] dreams of returning to his homeland."
[normal](
[normal]Our Beautiful Language
[normal], Grade 5, Part 1 (2011) p. 91)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal]4
[normal]. 
[normal]Espe
[normal]cially 
[normal]interesting in this context is the use of poems in order to strengthen among the students the sense that the return is inevitable. The poems add an emotional dimension to the issue and reveal one of its characteristics that is not usually evident in
[normal] other forms of discussion of the "Right of Return". 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Violent Character of "The Right of Return"[bold]3
[normal]5
[normal]. 
[normal]The "Right of Return", by definition, is a right, not a privilege. As such, it does not depend on 
[normal]Israel
[normal]'s good will and is not part of the peace proc
[normal]ess. Rather, it is presented as a decisive event, shrouded in an atmosphere of violence. The following two poems well exemplify that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal]6
[normal]. 
[normal]"
[normal]We Shall Return [Excerpts]
[normal]…
[normal]Tomorrow we shall come back and the ages shall listen
[normal]To the footfalls during the 
[normal]return
[normal]We shall return with the resounding storms
[normal]With the sacred lightening and the star
[normal]With the winged hopes and the songs
[normal]With the soaring vulture and the eagle
[normal]Yes! The thousands victims shall return
[normal]Victims of oppression shall open every door"
